      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Movie Star, Or a President?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher L Ball letter on tightness of presidential race (Oct 15 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Room for Error in the Final Weeks Before the Vote'' (front page, Oct. 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Room for Error in the Final Weeks Before the Vote'' (front page, Oct. 15):</p>
        <p>The nervousness of the campaigns with the tight presidential race is their own doing. The unwillingness of major-party presidential contenders to debate each other frequently after the primaries places excessive emphasis on their performance on only three occasions -- the debates right before the election.</p>
        <p>The candidates choose instead to take part in numerous staged events across the country, where they repeat the same trite claims to audiences made up mostly of people who have already decided to vote for them. And for this, they hire consultants?</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER L. BALL  Oxford, Iowa, Oct. 15, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a visiting instructor in political science, University of Iowa.</p>
      </block>
